Q.2 Introduction to DevSecOps in Fintech [15M]
(a) DevSecOPs in Fintech
Answer:
•	DevSecOps is the integration of security practices within the DevOps workflow.
•	Purpose:
•	Ensure continuous security during software development, testing, and deployment.
•	Shift security from reactive to proactive in fintech applications.
•	Key Benefits in Fintech:
1.	Early detection of vulnerabilities.
2.	Secure CI/CD pipelines.
3.	Compliance with regulatory standards (e.g., PCI DSS, RBI PSS).
________________________________________
(b) CI/CD Introduction
Answer:
•	CI/CD stands for Continuous Integration / Continuous Deployment.
•	CI (Continuous Integration):
•	Developers merge code into a shared repository frequently.
•	Automated tests are run to detect issues early.
•	CD (Continuous Deployment):
•	Code changes are automatically deployed to production after passing tests.
•	Role in Fintech:
•	Enables faster delivery of fintech applications.
•	Automates security checks and compliance validations in DevSecOps pipelines.
________________________________________
(c) SSDLC (Secure Software Development Life Cycle) Introduction
Answer:
•	SSDLC integrates security at every stage of the software development life cycle.
•	Phases:
1.	Requirements: Define security requirements and compliance standards.
2.	Design: Apply security architecture and threat modeling.
3.	Implementation: Write secure code using best practices.
4.	Testing: Conduct vulnerability scans, penetration testing.
5.	Deployment: Ensure secure configuration and environment hardening.
6.	Maintenance: Monitor, patch, and update systems continuously.
•	Importance in Fintech:
•	Protects sensitive financial data.
•	Ensures regulatory compliance and reduces risk of breaches.


