Q.1 Introduction to Software Composition Analysis (SCA) – Security Case Study [15M]
Answer:
Definition of SCA:
•	Software Composition Analysis (SCA) is the process of analyzing software applications to identify third-party and open-source components, and check for security vulnerabilities, license compliance, and outdated dependencies.
Importance in Fintech Security:
•	Fintech applications often use third-party libraries for payment processing, encryption, or analytics.
•	Vulnerable components can lead to data breaches, financial fraud, and regulatory non-compliance.
Case Study Example – Fintech Application:
•	Scenario: A digital wallet app uses multiple open-source libraries for encryption and payment integration.
•	Problem: One library had a known vulnerability that could allow attackers to steal cardholder data.
•	SCA Implementation:
1.	Scan all third-party libraries using SCA tools (e.g., Snyk, WhiteSource, Black Duck).
2.	Identify vulnerabilities and outdated versions.
3.	Apply patches or upgrade libraries.
4.	Continuously monitor new vulnerabilities.
•	Outcome:
•	Prevented potential data breaches.
•	Ensured PCI DSS compliance.
•	Improved customer trust and security posture.
Conclusion:
•	SCA is a proactive security measure in fintech that ensures software integrity and compliance, protecting financial data from risks arising from third-party components.
