Q.1 PSD2: Risks, Functions, and Scope [15M]
(a) What are the risks of using PSD2 [5M]
1.	Data Privacy Risk: Customer account information is shared with third-party providers, increasing potential exposure.
2.	Fraud Risk: Open APIs may be exploited by malicious actors if security is weak.
3.	Operational Risk: Banks need to maintain continuous availability of APIs, and any downtime affects payments.
4.	Compliance Risk: Failure to meet PSD2 regulatory requirements can result in fines and legal issues.
5.	Cybersecurity Risk: Increased attack surface due to multiple integration points with third-party providers.
________________________________________
(b) What are the functions of PSD2 [5M]
1.	Strong Customer Authentication (SCA): Ensures secure multi-factor authentication for payments.
2.	Open Banking APIs: Enables third-party providers (TPPs) to access bank account data securely.
3.	Fraud Detection: Monitors transactions in real-time to prevent unauthorized activities.
4.	Customer Consent Management: Ensures explicit approval for sharing account information.
5.	Transparency: Provides clear information on fees, transactions, and third-party access.
________________________________________
(c) What is the scope of PSD2? [5M]
•	PSD2 applies to:
1.	Payment service providers: Banks, fintech companies, and other authorized payment institutions.
2.	Payment types: Online payments, credit transfers, direct debits, card payments, and mobile payments.
3.	Geographical scope: European Union (EU) and European Economic Area (EEA) member countries.
4.	Third-party providers: Regulated access to account information (AISPs) and payment initiation (PISPs).
•	Objective: Promote innovation, competition, and security in digital payment services.
